inmutatum. If this word is the pass. participle of inmutare (cf. 275), it must mean ‘ changed,' as in has no negative force in com- position with verbs. Spengel takes it thus, explaining that Pamphilus‘ grief at the idea of marriage had changed into joy when he found that Chremes refused to allow the match. It is much better to consider it as an adjective, ‘unchanged’ The remark is intelligible enough, though not quite logical. Pamphilus, contrasting the changed purpose of Chremes with his own unchangcablc fidelity. speaks as if the one were the consequence of the other.
